[{"id":31611,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$0.56 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.24 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.96 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$0.4 \\mathrm{~nm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For a fcc unit cell\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& r=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} a}{4} \\\\\n& a=\\frac{4 r}{\\sqrt{2}}=2 \\sqrt{2} \\times 0.14=0.39 \\approx 0.4 \\mathrm{~nm}.\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31616,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Covalent solid","Molecular solid","Ionic solid","Network solid"],"answer":1,"solution":"Molecular solid is the best description of water in the solid phase. For example ice is hydrogen bonded molecular solid.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":31585,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Density =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>Volume</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=4&#160;&#160;&#8658;</mo><mi>fcc</mi></math>&nbsp;unit cell</p><p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>fcc</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p>unit cell&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>414</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>405</mn></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>143</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1675</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>143</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31596,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Tridymite","Quartz","Amorphous silica","Mica"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Piezoelectric materials are those that produce an electric current when placed under mechanical stress.</p><p>Quartz is used as a piezoelectric material in electronic devices.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31556,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>In given ionic compound anions form&nbsp;CCP lattice, And&nbsp;cation is&nbsp;present in octahedral void. Means this structure is similar to structure of NaCl. Which is also called rock salt structure.</p><p>Edge length =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>?</mo></math></p><p>In rock salt structure cations and anions are in contact along the edge of the cube.&nbsp;</p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>-</mo></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>102</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>181</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mn>283</mn></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>566</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pm</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31593,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;</p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> forms HCP&nbsp;as&nbsp;anions are larger in size.</p><p>From the formula&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>,</p><p>Number of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> atoms<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>,</p><p>Then, number of tetrahedral voids&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo></math>Tetrahedral voids<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>.</p><p>As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>'</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>'</mo></math>&nbsp;is occupying tetrahedral voids,</p><p>&nbsp;<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>3</mn> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;of&nbsp;tetrahedral voids<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><br />Therefore, formula of the compound<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31598,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/sYcNjSfYK1vJ1-7lYeJDTT1JH6M8C78jP3vZDjUk_ik.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/m5birlhlQ_wx5d7sSq94jxZ3AwI4eADsd_RJOgxrun8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gndji-E8KVd11Qz-gYYw1rIuA5HH8YIk6tst0WBB5Yo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Pi0VdcrPFI8O_JiVSEV-tyQRTrUZLG4EZD4CWW8LTyE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"When the magnetic moments align in a regular pattern with neighbouring spins pointing in opposite directions (as in d), the substance shows antiferromagnetism.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":31619,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{AB}_2$","$A_2 B_3$","$\\mathrm{A}_2 \\mathrm{~B}_5$","$A_2 B$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Effective no.of $A$ atoms $=\\frac{1}{8} \\times 8=1$\nEffective no.of $B$ atoms $=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 5$ (One is missing) $=\\frac{5}{2}$\nTherefore formula is $A_1 B_{\\frac{5}{2}}=A_2 B_5$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":31562,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>forms ccp structure that means number of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;atoms per unit cell&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;atoms per unit cell&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;(Octahedral voids), as number of octahedral voids will be equal to number of atoms per unit cell.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;removed&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>&nbsp;left&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p><p>Formula becomes&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31572,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is false","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is NOT the correct<br />explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>.</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is false but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is true.","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are true and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>."],"answer":1,"solution":"Sharp glass edges are heated to make them smooth. Because on heating glass melts and the surface of the liquid tends to take the rounded shape at the edges which has minimum surface area. This is called fire polishing of glass. Correct explanation for this is surface tension.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31564,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Number of effective atoms in HCP lattice is =6</p><p>Number of atoms of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p>Number of T.V. in h.c.p. =<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>Number</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atoms</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Number of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>&nbsp;atoms&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>&nbsp;atoms.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo></math>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mn>14</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>42</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>86</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p><p>Round off to the nearest integer = 43</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31581,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>All the corner atoms around&nbsp;body centre atom are nearest to that atom, so co-ordination number in this structure is eight.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31550,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The density of the crystal lattice can be calculated as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo></math>effective number of atoms in unit cell(For BCC=2 and FCC=4)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Molar mass</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></math>=Avogadro&#39;s number</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Edge length</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>FCC</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>BCC</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>90</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31587,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>4</mn></math>","<math><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math><mn>8</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>6</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>SC</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></math></p><p>[Atoms are only at the corners]</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>BCC</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;</p><p>[Atoms are at the corners and at the body center]</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>FCC</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>[Atoms are at the corners and at the face centers]</p><p>Here,&nbsp;Z=&nbsp;effective number of atoms in the unit cell.</p><p>Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>SC</mi></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>BCC</mi></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>FCC</mi></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/355fb20b-1fd9-4fda-a088-cbe666e07245-image15.png\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/374cb6e0-20e0-4cf2-8131-dab7a3574466-image16.png\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16c8d674-da79-4a5c-b202-6707fa0b21ca-image17.png\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>SC</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>BCC</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>FCC</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31586,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CsCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KBr</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZnS</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math> can exhibit both Schottky and Frenkel defect.</p><p>Schottky&nbsp;defect&nbsp;in&nbsp;<em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math></em>&nbsp;is exhibited due to the precipitation of both cations and anions. In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;ion is small in size and when removed&nbsp;from the lattice point, they can occupy the interstitial sites and, hence,&nbsp;shows&nbsp;both Frenkel and Schottky&nbsp;defects.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31574,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Ionic solid","Molecular solid","Metallic solid","Covalent solid"],"answer":3,"solution":"Covalent or network solid have very high melting point, and&nbsp;they are insulators in their solid and molten form.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31589,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><mn>90</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>45</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>","<math><mn>65</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d56858d2-34ef-457b-b322-d2b27b5e8080-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 217px;\" /></p><p>If radius of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math> radius of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> will be <math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math> . Atoms in the body diagonal touch.</p><p>Therefore:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math></p><p><math><mn>6</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> or <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Packing Efficiency<br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>/</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>216</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>90.5</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31625,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{A}\\mathrm{~B}$","$\\mathrm{A}_2 \\mathrm{~B}$","$\\mathrm{A}\\mathrm{~B}_3$","$\\mathrm{A}_3 \\mathrm{~B}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$$\nA=\\frac{1}{8} \\times 8=1\n$$\n(Corner)\n$\\mathrm{B}=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 6=3$\n(Face centre)\n$\\therefore \\mathrm{AB}_3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":31578,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>BCC</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p>so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></math></p><p>for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FCC</mi><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>33</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31549,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XY</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Atoms of Element&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>, are present in cubic close packing. In cubic close packing the number of atoms per unit cell is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>.</p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">So, the effective number of element&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>,&nbsp;per unit cell is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math></p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">Element&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>, are present at one third of the tetrahedral voids.</p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">Number of tetrahedral void&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math>Twice the number of atoms in unit cell</p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">Number of atoms of Element <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>&nbsp;are present&nbsp;unit cell&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace></math></p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">Formula of the compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31621,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$30 \\%$ and $26 \\%$","$26 \\%$ and $32 \\%$","$32 \\%$ and $48 \\%$","$48 \\%$ and $26 \\%$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Packing fraction of cubic close packing and body centred packing are $0.74$ and $0.68$ respectively.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":31571,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Carbon atoms occupy FCC lattice points as well as half of the tetrahedral voids</p><p>therefore number of carbon atoms atoms per unit cell <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31566,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Antiferromagnetism, type of magnetism in solids&nbsp;in which adjacent ions that behave as tiny magnets</p><p>Paramagnetism&nbsp;is a form of magnetism whereby some materials are weakly attracted by an externally applied magnetic field, and form internal, induced magnetic fields in the direction of the applied magnetic field.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MnO</mi></math>- Antiferromagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>- Paramagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi></math>- Diamagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>- Ferrimagnetism</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31599,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wqohdttvwxelulvpplrnivkpizxhkzpqnmerqjgdgujgzlbenf.jpeg\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 37px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/lvezhjwffqjlnzwvbwofmbsnespvekpcihgxrxumrrdqqwiilt.jpeg\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 35px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nfpgnmrapepobdvkmqhwgpmxoawvykffyhofmflrvaxoiganxe.jpeg\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 39px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qeapbnrexxznxbiprgrbfnznymqxrnjqjmqpupgrnhwptvstca.jpeg\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 40px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"Substances which are expected to possess para-magnetic or ferromagnetism on the basis of unpaired electrons, but actually they possess zero net magnetic moment are called anti-ferromagnetic substance.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":31559,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Schottky defect decreases the density of the substance.","Frenkel defect does not alter the density of the substance.","Interstitial defect increases the density of the substance.","Vacancy defect increases the density of the substance."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Frenkel Defect: This defect is shown by ionic solids. The smaller ion (usually cation) is dislocated from its normal site to an interstitial site. It creates a vacancy defect at its original site and an interstitial defect at its new location. Frenkel defect is also called dislocation defect. It does not change the density of the solid. In all other defects there is a change in the density.</p><p>In Schottky defect equal number of cation and anion are missing from their position so, it&nbsp;decreases the density of the substance.</p><p>In Interstitial defect extra atoms are present at interstitial position so, it&nbsp;increases the density of the substance.</p><p>Due to vacancy defect density of the substance will decrease. since atoms are missing from their positions.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31569,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Hexagonal","Orthorhombic","Monoclinic","Triclinic"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8800;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8800;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#947;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>&#8800;</mo><mi>&#946;</mi></math>&nbsp;are parameters of monoclinic unit cell.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31592,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$0.0432 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$0.0216 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$0.0305 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$0.4320 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Density $=\\frac{Z \\times M}{N_{A} \\times a^{3}}$\r\n\r\n$9 \\times 10^{3}=\\frac{4 \\times \\mathrm{M}}{\\left(200 \\times \\sqrt{2} \\times 10^{-12}\\right)^{3} 6 \\times 10^{23}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31547,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>A face-centered cubic (fcc) unit cell contains a component in the center of each face in addition to those at the corners of the cube. The atoms touch each other along the face diagonal.</p><p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>FCC</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p>A body-centered cubic (bcc) unit cell contains a component in the center of the cube&nbsp;in addition to those at the corners of the cube.&nbsp;The atoms touch each other along the body&nbsp;diagonal.<br /><br />For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>BCC</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31557,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Given ,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>ml</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>ZM</mi><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Volume of a unit cell = a<sup>3</sup>, where a is the edge length</p><p><strong>d</strong> is the density of the solid substance and<strong> M</strong> is the molar mass.</p><p>Mass of the unit cell = number of atoms in unit cell &times; mass of each atom =<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>(Here z is the number of atoms present in one unit cell and m is the mass of a single atom)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>64</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>86</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>97</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31568,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mfenced><mtext>&#160;only&#160;</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only"],"answer":3,"solution":"(A) Crystalline solids have definite arrangement of constituent particles and have long range order.<br />(C), (D) Different constituent particles of an amorphous solid have different bond strengths and soften over a range of temperatures.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null}]